  "prompt": "How does ngrok work?",
  "response": "ngrok is a tool that creates secure tunnels from public endpoints to locally running network services. Here's a breakdown of how it works:\n\n1. Basic Concept:\n- ngrok creates a secure tunnel from a public endpoint to a locally running web service\n- It exposes local servers to the internet without complex network configuration\n\n2. Tunnel Creation Process:\n```\nLocal Machine:\n[Your Local Server] --> ngrok client\n                       |\n                       v\nngrok's Cloud Servers: --> Public Endpoint\n```\n\n3. Key Steps:\n- When you start ngrok, it:\n  a) Connects to ngrok's cloud servers\n  b) Generates a random public URL\n  c) Forwards incoming requests to your local service\n\n4. Technical Details:\n- Uses reverse SSH tunneling\n- Creates an encrypted connection between your local machine and ngrok servers\n- Supports HTTP, HTTPS, TCP, and other protocols\n- Provides authentication and access control options\n\n5. Basic Usage Example:\n```bash\n# Start a local server on port 8080\npython -m http.server 8080\n\n# Run ngrok to expose local server\nngrok http 8080\n```\n\n6. Advanced Features:\n- Custom subdomain\n- IP restrictions\n- Web interface for monitoring connections\n- Persistent tunnels with paid plans\n\nEssentially, ngrok simplifies exposing local services to the internet securely and temporarily.",
